# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vitess
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vitess/architecture] The Vitess platform consists of a number of server processes, command-line utilities, and web-based utilities, backed by a consistent metadata store.
[src:vitess/architecture] Depending on the current state of your application, you could arrive at a full Vitess implementation through a number of different process flows.
[src:vitess/architecture] For example, if you're building a service from scratch, your first step with Vitess would be to define your database topology.
[src:vitess/architecture] However, if you need to scale your existing database, you'd likely start by deploying Vitess in Unmanaged mode.
[src:vitess/architecture] Vitess tools and servers are designed to help you whether you start with a complete fleet of databases or start small and scale over time.
[src:vitess/architecture] For smaller implementations, vttablet features like connection pooling and query rewriting help you get more from your existing hardware.
[src:vitess/architecture] Vitess' automation tools then provide additional benefits for larger implementations.
[src:vitess/architecture] For additional details on each of the components, see Concepts.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Vitess is a cloud-native horizontally-scalable distributed database system that is built around MySQL.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Vitess can achieve unlimited scaling through generalized sharding.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Vitess allows application code and database queries to remain agnostic to the distribution of data onto multiple database servers.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] With Vitess, you can even split and merge shards as your needs grow, with an atomic cutover step that takes only a few seconds.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Vitess was a core component of YouTube's database infrastructure from 2011, and grew to encompass tens of thousands of MySQL nodes.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Starting in 2015, Vitess was adopted by many other large companies, including Slack, Square (now Block), and JD.com.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] For more about Vitess, please visit vitess.io.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] If you are interested in contributing or participating in our monthly community meetings, please visit the Community page on our website.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] We also maintain a roadmap on our website.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Follow our blog for low-frequency updates like new features and releases.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] To report a problem, create a GitHub issue.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] For topics that are better discussed live, please join the Vitess Slack workspace.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] You may post any questions on the #general channel or join some of the special-interest channels.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] To report a security vulnerability, please email vitess-maintainers.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] See Security for a full outline of the security process.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] A third party security audit was performed by ADA Logics.
[src:vitess/main-readme-md] Unless otherwise noted, the Vitess source files are distributed under the Apache Version 2.0 license found in the LICENSE file.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL is free and open-source software under the terms of the GNU General Public License, and is also available under a variety of proprietary licenses.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL was owned and sponsored by the Swedish company MySQL AB, which was bought by Sun Microsystems (now Oracle Corporation).
[src:vitess/mysql] In 2010, when Oracle acquired Sun, Widenius forked the open-source MySQL project to create MariaDB.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL has stand-alone clients that allow users to interact directly with a MySQL database using SQL, but more often, MySQL is used with other programs to implement applications that need relational database capability.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL is a component of the LAMP web application software stack (and others), which is an acronym for *Linux, Apache, MySQL, Perl/PHP/Python*.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL is used by many database-driven web applications, including Drupal, Joomla, phpBB, and WordPress.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL is also used by many popular websites, including Facebook, Flickr, MediaWiki, Twitter, and YouTube.
[src:vitess/mysql] Its SQL parser is written in yacc, but it uses a home-brewed lexical analyzer.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL works on many system platforms, including AIX, BSDi, FreeBSD, HP-UX, ArcaOS, eComStation, IBM i, IRIX, Linux, macOS, Microsoft Windows, NetBSD, Novell NetWare, OpenBSD, OpenSolaris, OS/2 Warp, QNX, Oracle Solaris, Symbian, SunOS, SCO OpenServer, SCO UnixWare, Sanos and Tru64.
[src:vitess/mysql] The MySQL server software itself and the client libraries use dual-licensing distribution.
[src:vitess/mysql] They are offered under GPL version 2, or a proprietary license.
[src:vitess/mysql] Support can be obtained from the official manual.
[src:vitess/mysql] Free support additionally is available in different IRC channels and forums.
[src:vitess/mysql] Oracle offers paid support via its MySQL Enterprise products.
[src:vitess/mysql] They differ in the scope of services and in price.
[src:vitess/mysql] Additionally, a number of third party organisations exist to provide support and services.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL has received positive reviews, and reviewers noticed it "performs extremely well in the average case" and that the "developer interfaces are there, and the documentation (not to mention feedback in the real world via Web sites and the like) is very, very good".
[src:vitess/mysql] It has also been tested to be a "fast, stable and true multi-user, multi-threaded SQL database server".
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL was created by a Swedish company, MySQL AB, founded by Swedes David Axmark and Allan Larsson, along with Finn Michael "Monty" Widenius.
[src:vitess/mysql] Original development of MySQL by Widenius and Axmark began in 1994.
[src:vitess/mysql] The first version of MySQL appeared on 23 May 1995.
[src:vitess/mysql] It was initially created for personal usage from mSQL based on the low-level language ISAM, which the creators considered too slow and inflexible.
[src:vitess/mysql] They created a new SQL interface, while keeping the same API as mSQL.
[src:vitess/mysql] By keeping the API consistent with the mSQL system, many developers were able to use MySQL instead of the (proprietarily licensed) mSQL antecedent.
[src:vitess/mysql] Work on version 6 stopped after the Sun Microsystems acquisition.
[src:vitess/mysql] The MySQL Cluster product uses version 7.
[src:vitess/mysql] The decision was made to jump to version 8 as the next major version number.
[src:vitess/mysql] On 15 June 2001, NuSphere sued MySQL AB, TcX DataKonsult AB and its original authors Michael ("Monty") Widenius and David Axmark in U.S.
[src:vitess/mysql] District Court in Boston for "breach of contract, tortious interference with third party contracts and relationships and unfair competition".
[src:vitess/mysql] In 2002, MySQL AB sued Progress NuSphere for copyright and trademark infringement in United States district court.
[src:vitess/mysql] NuSphere had allegedly violated MySQL AB's copyright by linking MySQL's GPL'ed code with NuSphere Gemini table without being in compliance with the license.
[src:vitess/mysql] After a preliminary hearing before Judge Patti Saris on 27 February 2002, the parties entered settlement talks and eventually settled.
[src:vitess/mysql] In October 2005, Oracle Corporation acquired Innobase OY, the Finnish company that developed the third-party InnoDB storage engine that allows MySQL to provide such functionality as transactions and foreign keys.
[src:vitess/mysql] After the acquisition, an Oracle press release mentioned that the contracts that make the company's software available to MySQL AB would be due for renewal (and presumably renegotiation) some time in 2006.
[src:vitess/mysql] During the MySQL Users Conference in April 2006, MySQL AB issued a press release that confirmed that MySQL AB and Innobase OY agreed to a "multi-year" extension of their licensing agreement.
[src:vitess/mysql] In February 2006, Oracle Corporation acquired Sleepycat Software, makers of the Berkeley DB, a database engine providing the basis for another MySQL storage engine.
[src:vitess/mysql] This had little effect, as Berkeley DB was not widely used, and was dropped (due to lack of use) in MySQL 5.1.12, a pre-GA release of MySQL 5.1 released in October 2006.
[src:vitess/mysql] In January 2008, Sun Microsystems bought MySQL AB for $1 billion.
[src:vitess/mysql] In April 2009, Oracle Corporation entered into an agreement to purchase Sun Microsystems, then owners of MySQL copyright and trademark.
[src:vitess/mysql] Sun's board of directors unanimously approved the deal.
[src:vitess/mysql] It was also approved by Sun's shareholders, and by the U.S. government on 20 August 2009.
[src:vitess/mysql] On 14 December 2009, Oracle pledged to continue to enhance MySQL as it had done for the previous four years.
[src:vitess/mysql] A movement against Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, to "Save MySQL" from Oracle was started by one of the MySQL AB founders, Monty Widenius.
[src:vitess/mysql] The petition of 50,000+ developers and users called upon the European Commission to block approval of the acquisition.
[src:vitess/mysql] At the same time, some Free Software opinion leaders (including Pamela Jones of Groklaw, Jan Wildeboer and Carlo Piana, who also acted as co-counsel in the merger regulation procedure) advocated for the unconditional approval of the merger.
[src:vitess/mysql] As part of the negotiations with the European Commission, Oracle committed that MySQL server will continue until at least 2015 to use the dual-licensing strategy long used by MySQL AB, with proprietary and GPL versions available.
[src:vitess/mysql] The antitrust of the EU had been "pressuring it to divest MySQL as a condition for approval of the merger".
[src:vitess/mysql] But the US Department of Justice, at the request of Oracle, pressured the EU to approve the merger unconditionally.
[src:vitess/mysql] The European Commission eventually unconditionally approved Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB on 21 January 2010.
[src:vitess/mysql] In January 2010, before Oracle's acquisition of MySQL AB, Monty Widenius started a GPL-only fork, MariaDB.
[src:vitess/mysql] MariaDB is based on the same code base as MySQL server 5.5 and aims to maintain compatibility with Oracle-provided versions.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL is offered under two different editions: the open source MySQL Community Server and the proprietary Enterprise Server.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL Enterprise Server is differentiated by a series of proprietary extensions which install as server plugins, but otherwise shares the version numbering system and is built from the same code base.
[src:vitess/mysql] The developers release minor updates of the MySQL Server approximately every two months.
[src:vitess/mysql] The sources can be obtained from MySQL's website or from MySQL's GitHub repository, both under the GPL license.
[src:vitess/mysql] When using some storage engines other than the default of InnoDB, MySQL does not comply with the full SQL standard for some of the implemented functionality, including foreign key references.
[src:vitess/mysql] Check constraints are parsed but ignored by all storage engines before MySQL version 8.0.15.
[src:vitess/mysql] Up until MySQL 5.7, triggers are limited to one per action / timing, meaning that at most one trigger can be defined to be executed after an INSERT operation, and one before INSERT on the same table.
[src:vitess/mysql] Before MySQL 8.0.28, inbuilt functions like UNIX_TIMESTAMP() would return 0 after 03:14:07 UTC on 19 January 2038.
[src:vitess/mysql] In 2017, an attempt to solve the problem was submitted, but was not used for the final solution that was shipped in 2022.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL can be built and installed manually from source code, but it is more commonly installed from a binary package unless special customizations are required.
[src:vitess/mysql] On most Linux distributions, the package management system can download and install MySQL with minimal effort, though further configuration is often required to adjust security and optimization settings.
[src:vitess/mysql] Though MySQL began as a low-end alternative to more powerful proprietary databases, it has gradually evolved to support higher-scale needs as well.
[src:vitess/mysql] It is still most commonly used in small to medium scale single-server deployments, either as a component in a LAMP-based web application or as a standalone database server.
[src:vitess/mysql] Much of MySQL's appeal originates in its relative simplicity and ease of use, which is enabled by an ecosystem of open source tools such as phpMyAdmin.
[src:vitess/mysql] In the medium range, MySQL can be scaled by deploying it on more powerful hardware, such as a multi-processor server with gigabytes of memory.
[src:vitess/mysql] There are, however, limits to how far performance can scale on a single server ('scaling up'), so on larger scales, multi-server MySQL ('scaling out') deployments are required to provide improved performance and reliability.
[src:vitess/mysql] A typical high-end configuration can include a powerful source database (formerly known as master database) which handles data write operations and is replicated to multiple replicas (formerly known as slaves) that handle all read operations.
[src:vitess/mysql] The source server continually pushes binlog events to connected replicas so in the event of failure a replica can be promoted to become the new source, minimizing downtime.
[src:vitess/mysql] Further improvements in performance can be achieved by caching the results from database queries in memory using memcached, or breaking down a database into smaller chunks called shards which can be spread across a number of distributed server clusters.
[src:vitess/mysql] Oracle MySQL offers a high availability solution with a mix of tools including the MySQL router and the MySQL shell.
[src:vitess/mysql] They are based on Group Replication, open source tools.
[src:vitess/mysql] MariaDB offers a similar offer in terms of products.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL can also be run on cloud computing platforms such as Microsoft Azure, Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud, and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.
[src:vitess/mysql] In this implementation, cloud users can upload a machine image of their own with MySQL installed, or use a ready-made machine image with an optimized installation of MySQL on it, such as the one provided by Amazon EC2.
[src:vitess/mysql] Some cloud platforms offer MySQL "as a service".
[src:vitess/mysql] In this configuration, application owners do not have to install and maintain the MySQL database on their own.
[src:vitess/mysql] Instead, the database service provider takes responsibility for installing and maintaining the database, and application owners pay according to their usage.
[src:vitess/mysql] Notable cloud-based MySQL services are the Amazon Relational Database Service; Oracle MySQL HeatWave Database Service, Azure Database for MySQL, Rackspace; HP Converged Cloud; Heroku and Jelastic.
[src:vitess/mysql] In this model the database service provider takes responsibility for maintaining the host and database.
[src:vitess/mysql] A graphical user interface (GUI) is a type of interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices or programs through graphical icons and visual indicators such as secondary notation, as opposed to text-based interfaces, typed command labels or text navigation.
[src:vitess/mysql] Third-party proprietary and free graphical administration applications (or "front ends") are available that integrate with MySQL and enable users to work with database structure and data visually.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL Workbench is the integrated environment for MySQL.
[src:vitess/mysql] It was developed by MySQL AB, and enables users to graphically administer MySQL databases and visually design database structures.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL Workbench is available in three editions, the regular free and open source *Community Edition* which may be downloaded from the MySQL website, and the proprietary *Standard Edition* which extends and improves the feature set of the Community Edition, and the MySQL Cluster CGE.
[src:vitess/mysql] A command-line interface is a means of interacting with a computer program where the user issues commands to the program by typing in successive lines of text (command lines).
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL ships with many command line tools, from which the main interface is the mysql client.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL Utilities is a set of utilities designed to perform common maintenance and administrative tasks.
[src:vitess/mysql] Originally included as part of the MySQL Workbench, the utilities are a stand-alone download available from Oracle.
[src:vitess/mysql] Percona Toolkit is a cross-platform toolkit for MySQL, developed in Perl.
[src:vitess/mysql] Percona Toolkit can be used to prove replication is working correctly, fix corrupted data, automate repetitive tasks, and speed up servers.
[src:vitess/mysql] Percona Toolkit is included with several Linux distributions such as CentOS and Debian, and packages are available for Fedora and Ubuntu as well.
[src:vitess/mysql] Percona Toolkit was originally developed as Maatkit, but as of late 2011, Maatkit is no longer developed.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL shell is a tool for interactive use and administration of the MySQL database.
[src:vitess/mysql] It supports JavaScript, Python or SQL modes and it can be used for administration and access purposes.
[src:vitess/mysql] Many programming languages with language-specific APIs include libraries for accessing MySQL databases.
[src:vitess/mysql] These include MySQL Connector/Net for .NET/CLI Languages, and the JDBC driver for Java.
[src:vitess/mysql] MySQL offers Connector/C++ for interfacing with C++ in namespace `mysqlx`.
[src:vitess/mysql] In addition, an ODBC interface called MySQL Connector/ODBC allows additional programming languages that support the ODBC interface to communicate with a MySQL database, such as ASP or ColdFusion.
[src:vitess/mysql] The HTSQL – URL-based query method also ships with a MySQL adapter, allowing direct interaction between a MySQL database and any web client via structured URLs.
[src:vitess/mysql] Other drivers exists for languages like Python or Node.js.
[src:vitess/mysql] MariaDB is a community-developed fork of the MySQL relational database management system intended to remain free under the GNU GPL.
[src:vitess/mysql] The fork has been led by the original developers of MySQL, who forked it due to concerns over its acquisition by Oracle.
[src:vitess/mysql] Percona Server for MySQL, forked by Percona, aims to retain close compatibility to the official MySQL releases.
[src:vitess/mysql] Also included in Percona Server for MySQL is XtraDB, Percona's fork of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:vitess/mysql] Drizzle was a free software/open source relational database management system (DBMS) that was forked from the now-defunct 6.0 development branch of the MySQL DBMS.
[src:vitess/mysql] Like MySQL, Drizzle had a client/server architecture and uses SQL as its primary command language.
[src:vitess/mysql] Drizzle was distributed under version 2 and 3 of the GNU General Public License (GPL) with portions, including the protocol drivers and replication messaging under the BSD license.
[src:vitess/mysql] Thus, WebScaleSQL opened a path toward deduplicating the efforts each company had been putting into maintaining its own branch of MySQL, and toward bringing together more developers.
[src:vitess/mysql] By combining the efforts of these companies and incorporating various changes and new features into MySQL, WebScaleSQL aimed at supporting the deployment of MySQL in large-scale environments.
[src:vitess/mysql] The project's source code is licensed under version 2 of the GNU General Public License, and is hosted on GitHub.
[src:vitess/mysql] The OurDelta distribution, created by the Australian company Open Query (later acquired by Catalyst IT Australia), had two versions: 5.0, which was based on MySQL, and 5.1, which was based on MariaDB.
[src:vitess/mysql] It included patches developed by Open Query and by other notable members of the MySQL community including Jeremy Cole and Google.
[src:vitess/mysql] Once the patches were incorporated into the MariaDB mainline, OurDelta's objectives were achieved and OurDelta passed on its build and packaging toolchain to Monty Program (now MariaDB Plc).
[src:vitess/page] Talks, presentations and podcasts for your learning!
[src:vitess/page] Everything you need to know about scaling MySQL with Vitess.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:vitess/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:vitess/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:vitess/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:vitess/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:vitess/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:vitess/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:vitess/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:vitess/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:vitess/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:vitess/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:vitess/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:vitess/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:vitess/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:vitess/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:vitess/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:vitess/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:vitess/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:vitess/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:vitess/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:vitess/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:vitess/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:vitess/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:vitess/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:vitess/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:vitess/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:vitess/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:vitess/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:vitess/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:vitess/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:vitess/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:vitess/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:vitess/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:vitess/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:vitess/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:vitess/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:vitess/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:vitess/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:vitess/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:vitess/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:vitess/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:vitess/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:vitess/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] A **database shard**, or simply a **shard**, is a horizontal partition of data within a database or search engine.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Each shard may be held on a separate database server instance in order to spread across multiple servers.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Some data in a database may remain present in all shards, while other data is stored in only one shard.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] In such cases, each shard acts as the single source for its subset of data.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] There are numerous advantages to the horizontal partitioning of data.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Since tables are divided and distributed into multiple servers, the total number of rows in each table in each database is reduced.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] This reduces index size, which generally improves search performance.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] A database shard can be placed on separate hardware, and multiple shards can be placed on multiple machines.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] This enables the distribution of a database across a large number of machines, which can significantly improve performance.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] In addition, if the database shard is based on some real-world segmentation of the data (e.g., European customers v.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] American customers) it may be possible to infer the appropriate shard membership easily and automatically, and to query only the relevant shard.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Although it has long been implemented through manual coding (especially where rows have an obvious grouping, as in the customer region example above), this approach is often inflexible.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] There is a desire to support sharding automatically, both in terms of adding code support for it, and for identifying candidates to be sharded separately.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Consistent hashing is a technique used in sharding to distribute large loads across multiple smaller services and servers.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Where distributed computing is used to separate load between multiple servers (either for performance or reliability reasons), a sharding approach may also be useful.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] In the 2010s, sharding of execution capacity, as well as the more traditional sharding of data, emerged as a potential approach to address performance and scalability challenges in blockchains.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Recent academic work has proposed protocols such as Cerberus to address cross-shard atomicity by braiding consensus across multiple shards, allowing transactions to affect multiple partitions simultaneously without requiring a global lock.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Horizontal partitioning splits one or more tables by row, usually within a *single* instance of a schema and a database server.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] It partitions the relevant table or tables in the same way, but does so across potentially *multiple* instances of the schema.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] An advantage is that the search load for the large partitioned table can be distributed across multiple servers (logical or physical), rather than only across multiple indexes on a same logical server.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Splitting shards across multiple isolated instances requires more than simple horizontal partitioning.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] The expected gains in efficiency would be reduced if querying the database required *multiple* instances to be accessed just to retrieve a simple dimension table.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Beyond partitioning, sharding therefore involves distributing large, partitionable tables across servers, while smaller tables are replicated in full on each server.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] This is also why sharding is related to a shared-nothing architecture—once sharded, each shard can reside in a separate logical schema instance, physical database server, data center, or geographic region.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is intended to minimize the need for cross-shard access by partitioning data across independent shards.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] This makes replication across multiple servers easier (simple horizontal partitioning does not).
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] It is also useful for worldwide distribution of applications, where communications links between data centers might otherwise become a bottleneck.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] There is also a requirement for some notification and replication mechanism between schema instances, so that unpartitioned tables remain as closely synchronized as the application requires.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] This is a complex architectural choice in sharded systems: approaches range from making these tables effectively read-only (with updates that are rare and batched), to dynamically replicated tables (at the cost of reducing some of the distribution benefits of sharding), and many options in between.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Sharding a database table before it has been optimized locally can introduce unnecessary complexity.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Sharding is generally recommended when other optimization strategies have proven insufficient.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] The added complexity of database sharding can result in several potential challenges.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Richard Garriott, creator of *Ultima Online*, recalled that the term originated during the production of the game, specifically in creating a self-regulating, virtual ecology system.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] Players were able to interact and harvest in-game resources via the internet, which disrupted the balance of the system.
[src:vitess/shard-database-architecture] The feature was later removed after several months of testing.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Vitess is a database solution for deploying, scaling and managing large clusters of open-source database instances.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] It currently supports MySQL and Percona Server for MySQL.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] It's architected to run as effectively in a public or private cloud architecture as it does on dedicated hardware.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] It combines and extends many important SQL features with the scalability of a NoSQL database.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Migrating from bare-metal or VMs to a private or public cloud.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Deploying and managing a large number of SQL database instances.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Vitess includes compliant JDBC and Go database drivers using a native query protocol.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Additionally, it implements the MySQL server protocol which is compatible with virtually any other language.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Vitess served all YouTube database traffic for over five years.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] Many enterprises have now adopted Vitess for their production needs.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] The following sections compare Vitess to two common alternatives, a vanilla MySQL implementation and a NoSQL implementation.
[src:vitess/whatisvitess] If you're considering a NoSQL solution primarily because of concerns about the scalability of MySQL, Vitess might be a more appropriate choice for your application.
